    pearls: ["ROM exercises prevent contractures, which develop rapidly — flexion contractures can begin within 48-72 hours of immobility","Always support the limb above and below the joint during passive ROM to prevent injury","Never force a joint past the point of resistance — this can cause soft tissue damage, fracture, or heterotopic ossification","Active ROM is always preferred over passive ROM because it also maintains muscle strength","Combine ROM exercises with repositioning every 2 hours for comprehensive immobility management","DVT risk increases with immobility — ROM exercises promote venous return and reduce clot formation"],
    quiz: [{ question: "A nurse is performing passive ROM exercises on a comatose patient's right knee. The nurse feels resistance at 90 degrees of flexion. What is the correct action?", options: ["Force the joint past the resistance to gain full range","Stop at the point of resistance and document the limited range","Skip the knee and focus on other joints","Perform ROM only once per week to allow healing"], correct: 1, rationale: "Never force a joint past the point of resistance during ROM exercises. Forcing can cause tissue damage, pain, fracture, or heterotopic ossification. The nurse should stop, document the limited range, and report it so physical therapy can develop a plan to gradually improve flexibility." },{ question: "Which type of ROM exercise is appropriate for a patient who is completely paralyzed below the waist?", options: ["Active ROM — the patient should try harder","Active-assistive ROM — the nurse provides some help","Passive ROM — the nurse performs all movement for the patient","No ROM exercises are needed for paralyzed limbs"], correct: 2, rationale: "Passive ROM is appropriate when the patient cannot initiate any voluntary movement. The nurse or therapist performs all joint movements to maintain flexibility, prevent contractures, and promote circulation. Without ROM exercises, contractures develop rapidly and can be permanent." }]
